english:
  title: Preface to the Collected Poems of Seon Tan, the Buddhist Monk of the Eastern Sea
  author: Kang Seok-deok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I once heard that Seon Tan, a monk of Goryeo, excelled in both poetry and the zither. I saw his early spring poem:

    The sound of strings shatters the stream beyond the bamboo grove,
    Watercolor strokes dot the mountains shrouded in mist.
    I halt my horse and gaze again and again—
    Larks rise and fall upon the spring wind.

    I thought the composition lacked grandeur, the sentiment lacked depth, and the execution lacked refinement. Why then is he celebrated so greatly by posterity? Recently, I obtained from my elder brother Chi-suk a large collection of miscellaneous poems, not knowing whose work they were. Among them was this so-called early spring poem, and I suspected it had merely been appended by someone. I did not believe this represented Seon Tan's true work.

    But as I read further through the collection, I found poems such as "Farewell to the Magistrate of Wansan," which reads:

    The spring wind carries infinite longing,
    I tell it to the monk Seon Tan beyond the river south.

    And "To Yun Saeng":

    Tan, who ate humble greens his whole life through...

    And "On the Zither":

    The tattered instrument yields no sweetness to play.

    Since no other Eastern monk is known for fame in both zither and poetry save for this master, this collection must be his complete work. My former doubts were thus dispelled.

    Now, reading and rereading these verses, when beauty stirs my heart, I cannot contain myself. Some pieces are like a young nobleman in the brothels, indulging wildly—lacking propriety, yet with an earthy charm, like a farmer's simple talk, wanting in refinement. Other passages surge with bold freedom, like the carefree nobility of old families—gallant and unburdened, possessed of true elegance. And there are four or five poems of crystalline purity and serene depth, where heaven's own artistry shines forth. Such work surely merits praise from masters of literature like the great scholar Yi-jae.

    That early spring poem was merely a casual composition.

    Alas, my nature inclines toward freedom and solitude. I love those who dwell in mountains and forests. How fortunate that, born centuries later, I have found these verses scattered among old fragments! Is this not a meeting of kindred spirits across time? Surely this is what is meant by encountering one another, morning and evening, beyond the ages. Fearing these poems might otherwise perish and his name fade into obscurity, I have gathered them into one volume and titled it "The Collected Poems of Seon Tan, the Buddhist Monk of the Eastern Sea." I entrust this work to my friend and historian Nam Gyeong-so, that it may serve future scholars and fulfill my lifelong wish to praise the worthy.

    How many talented and noble persons lie buried in mountains and marshes, their names unknown and unsung? Should we not lament this deeply?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Yi-jae (益齋) was a renowned Goryeo scholar and literary master whose patronage validated Seon Tan's work.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to "Wang and Xie families" alludes to the refined aristocratic elite of classical China, known for their poetic sensibility and unbridled elegance.
  - key: ''
    value: The phrase "meeting morning and evening" reflects the classical Chinese concept that true kinship transcends temporal distance.
